a) Implement PCA¶

In [ ]:
# n:= number of PC
def PCA(data, n):
    # center by subtracting the mean
    centered = (data - np.mean(data, axis=0))
    # covariance matrix of centered data, columns are variables
    cov = np.cov(centered, rowvar=False)
    # from covariance matrix decompose eigen values and vectors
    eigenVals, eigenVecs = eig(cov)
    # sort in Descending order
    eigenValsDESC = np.sort(eigenVals)[::-1]
    # same order for eigenvectors
    eigenVecsDESC = eigenVecs[:,np.argsort(eigenVals)[::-1]]
    # choose n components
    sub = eigenVecsDESC[:, 0:n]
    subLow = eigenVecsDESC[:, -n:]
    # return reduced
    reduced = np.dot(sub.T, centered.T).T
    reducedLowest = np.dot(subLow.T, centered.T).T
    
    varExplained = eigenValsDESC
    varExplainedRatio = (varExplained / np.sum(varExplained))
     
    return reduced, reducedLowest, varExplained, varExplainedRatio

b)¶

Below code demonstrates the usage of the function PCA() above, implementing Principle Component Analysis.

Comparison is made between the results of the own implementation and the results from sklearn package. Although neither values of explained variance nor explained variance ratio are exactly the same as the values delivered by mentioned package, their difference is negligable.

Explained Variance¶

In the context of PCA Explained Variance is a measure of variability that tells us how much information contained in the data from given dataset is covered (explained) by each of the principal components (eigenvectors). It introduces a notion of importance among feature variables. In other words, it tells us which variables should be kept and which can be safely discarded without loosing too much information.

Explained Variance Ratio¶

Explained variance Ratio is the proportion of explained variance to the sum of values of Explained Variance, i.e. the ratio illustrates a percentage of "importance" to given principal component.

Interpretation¶

Based on the plotted results above, we can observe that the first plot on the left, projecting the data along the first 2 principle components (sorted array in descending order) has a better seperation of samples than the second plot (right). This is because the first PC explains ~ 83.5 % of variance and second explains ~ 15.7% of variance. In contrast, the last 2 PCs (6th and 7th) explains only ~ 0.012 % and ~ 0.00029 % of variance, respectively.

b) clustering techniques¶

DBSCAN¶

DBSCAN works best for clustering data sets that are not necessarily radial. The DBSCAN algorithm accepts epsilon a "distance radius" surrounding each data point and minimum number of samples for a point tobe considered a core point and accordingly the group to be considered a cluster. For best results it is neccessary to have a rough idea about the shape of data. It favors shapes that can be distinct, being immune to outliers unlike other clustering algorithms. Used parameters must be always selected based on the "distances" of the data and hence are fine-tuned as a result of multiple iterations of trial & error.

In theory DBSCAN would be my first choice if I did not know the shape of the data for the reason of being immune to outliers.

K-Means¶

K-means has been chosen as it is foundational clustering algorithm and arguably the most well-known among the alternatives. Algorithm clusters the best datasets that are have radial clusters, requiring the number of clusters (k) to be specified beforehand. Accordingly, number of clusters must be known in advance to produce meaningful results.

Average Link¶

Average Link also known as Agglomerative Clustering accepts number of clusters that need to be known in advance for the algorithm to perform well. The technique utilizes 3 properties:

  • Single Linkage : distance between the closest members of 2 distinct clusters
  • Complete Linkage : greatest possible distance of 2 members of 2 distinct clusters
  • Average Linkage : average distance calculated based on distances between all points of 2 clusters

The distance is typically calculated as Euclidean distance.

print("NMI: Normalized Mutual Information \nRMI: Random Index \n\n---\n")
def Evaluate(clusteringMethod, predicted, originalLabels):
    index = 0
    for i in originalLabels:
        print(f'NMI for {clusteringMethod} on dataset {index + 1}:'.ljust(48) + f'{normalized_mutual_info_score(predicted[index],i)}')
        print(f'ARS for {clusteringMethod} on dataset {index + 1}:'.ljust(48) + f'{adjusted_rand_score(predicted[index],i)}')
        index += 1
    print("---")

d) Result discussion¶

For dataset from dataset1_noCluster15.csv the best results were given by K-means, EM algorithms and Average Link respectively. The reason for their great performance is that the spatial form of all clusters was radial which is a desirable property for mentioned algorithms. Despite the last place, considering the more general approach of the DBSCAN algorithm, it has produced satisfactory results as well.

For dataset from dataset2_noCluster2.csv likewise for the first dataset, K-Means clustered the data perfectly. EM and Average linking respectively, have performed worse, although still with satisfactory results. It is evident that DBSCAN is not an optimal clustering algorithm for this dataset as it missclassified over half of the samples. The number of specified clusters is a clear advantage as the problem lies within the spatial composition of the data. For an observer it is challenging to find a seperating rule as the data seem to be 1 large cluster.

For dataset from dataset3_noCluster2.csv DBSCAN clusters the data perfectly. The scatter plot of the data is an example where DBSCAN performs the best. DBSCAN is advantageous to using other algoritms used that perform better on the radial compositions of data points.

For dataset from dataset4_noCluster2.csv the best results are produced by Expectation Maximization algorithm followed by DBSCAN. The shape of the data is not necessarily evenly distributed, but we can observe two rather different distinguishible shapes. That's why mentioned algorithms vastly outperform K-Means.

import math

# import and preprocess data
database = []
items = set()
relativeMinSupp = 0.01

# put transactions in a database
with open("songs.txt", "r") as file:
    for user in file:
        database.append(set(user.replace("\n", "").split(";")))

# create set of all songs 
for transaction in database:
    items.update(transaction)

#calculate absolute support
absMinSupp = math.floor(relativeMinSupp * len(items))

a) length 1 frequent sets¶

In [ ]:
def countSupport(item, database, multiple=False):
    support = 0
    if (multiple is False):
        itemSet = set([item])
    else:
        itemSet = set(item)
    for transaction in database:
        if(itemSet.issubset(transaction)):
            support += 1
    return support

def getL1(items, database):
    L1 = []
    for song in items:
        support = countSupport(song, database)
        if(support > absMinSupp):
            L1.append({support:song})
    return L1

L1 = getL1(items, database)

form="%s\n"
with open("oneItems.txt",'w') as file:
    for i in L1:
        for key, value in i.items():
            file.write('{}:{}\n'.format(key,''.join(value)))

b) All frequent itemset¶

In [ ]:
from itertools import combinations

# Return candidate with insufficient support
def getL1Removed(items, database):
    L1removed = set()
    for song in items:
        # generate combinations
        support = countSupport(song, database)
        if(support <= absMinSupp):
            L1removed.add(song)
    return L1removed

# Get candidates for set of size n:=membesInSet            
def generateCandidates(items, database, membersInSet):
    C = set()
    for transaction in database:
        for i in list(combinations(transaction, membersInSet)):
            C.add(frozenset(i))
    return C

# frequent Itemsets based on the supplied candidates and DB
def getFrequent(candidateSet, database):
    res = []
    for i in candidateSet:
        counter = 0
        for j in database:
            if (i.issubset(j)):
                counter += 1
        if(counter > absMinSupp):
            res.append({counter:i})
    return res

import copy

L2DB = copy.deepcopy(database)
L1Removed = getL1Removed(items, database)

# optimization by deleting irrelevant itemsets
for transaction in L2DB: 
    for removed in L1Removed:
        if(removed in transaction):
            transaction.remove(removed)

# Length 2 Itemsets
# disjunction a.k.a. set difference
updatedItemset = items - L1Removed
C2 = generateCandidates(updatedItemset, L2DB, 2)

L2 = getFrequent(C2, L2DB)
print(L2)

c) Song Recommendation for a User¶

for the set of songs Hotel California and Knockin' On Heaven's Door (support 26)

In [ ]:
userPref = {"Hotel California", "Knockin' On Heaven's Door"}

L3VSets = [list(i.values())[0] for i in L3]

recommend = []

for i in L3VSets:
    if userPref.issubset(i):
        # set difference
        recommend.append(i - userPref)      
        
# Final Verdict 
index = 0
for i in recommend:
    print(f'Recommended song #{index} for the user: {list(i)[0]}')
    index += 1

Recommended song #0 for the user: Look What The Cat Dragged In
Recommended song #1 for the user: Stairway To Heaven

Based on the results of the Apriori Algorithm implemented above, there are 2 songs that could be recommended to the user:

  • Stairway To Heaven (confidence = 19 / 26 ~ 73 %)
  • Look What The Cat Dragged In (confidence = 19 / 26 ~ 73 %)

The corresponding supports needed to calculate confidence can be easily retrieved by searching through the patterns.txt containing Itemsets and their support.

For calculating confidence the following formula has been used: In simple terms, it represents how often items in itemset Y appear in transactions that contain items of itemset X.

Accordingly, both Stairway To Heaven and Look What The Cat Dragged In appear in itemsets that also contain preferred items by the user Hotel California Knockin' On Heaven's Door.

In other words, mentioned itemsets have the following properties:

  • { Stairway To Heaven, Hotel California, Knockin' On Heaven's Door } has support 19
  • { Look What The Cat Dragged In, Hotel California, Knockin' On Heaven's Door } has support 19

The itemset {Hotel California, Knockin' On Heaven's Door} appears 26 times and hence has support 26.

For that reason, the confidence of both dataset is identical being conf = 19/26 ~ 73 %.
